## 6) Operational SOP — Volunteers (Front-line workflow)
Volunteers do NOT need to know schema details.

### 6.1 Create a work order (any authenticated volunteer)
When you see an issue:
1) Open the Work Orders app (DB UI).
2) Click “New Work Order”.
3) Fill in:
   - Work Area (where it is)
   - Task Type (Repair / Build / Setup / etc.)
   - Problem (what’s wrong)
   - Notes (extra detail)
   - Photo URL (optional) / attach photo (if enabled)
   - Target Year (optional if it’s a future plan item)
   - Urgency (optional if you know it; otherwise leave blank)
   - Display link (if you can find it)
4) Save.

**Important:** volunteers should not assign work orders.

### 6.2 Update a work order (while working)
- Add notes (or comments) describing findings and progress.
- Don’t overwrite the original problem statement; add detail in notes/comments.

### 6.3 Complete a work order (button)
When the work is finished:
1) Open the work order
2) Click **Complete**
3) Enter “what was done” (completion notes)
4) Save

The system will automatically:
- stamp completion date/time (now)
- record who completed it (your email / person record)

---

## 7) Operational SOP — Managers (triage + assignment)
### 7.1 Triage views (saved filters)
Managers should have saved views:
- Unassigned Open Work Orders
- Urgent Open Work Orders (urgency P0–P2)
- Target Year = 2026 Plan Items
- Needs Triage (urgency null + target_year null)

### 7.2 Assign work
1) Open the work order
2) Add one or more assignees
3) Optionally set urgency and/or target year
4) Save

### 7.3 Assign at creation time (manager-only)
- If a manager is creating the work order, they may assign immediately.

